\begin_layout Abstract
This is a continuation of Part Three: a description of free-falling flashlights
 and observers.
 The goal here is to solve the general case, for the Schwarzschild solution,
 but in coordinates valid across the event horizon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general discussion can be found in Part Three; I'll just recap here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A traditional caculation demonstrates what the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fixed stars
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 look like to a freely-falling, infalling observer.
 The current project is to update this, and consider the case of flashlights
 that are also freely falling.
 What does the observer see then? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The project is made intersting by considering the flashlight to be a smart
 radio device that can communicate flashlight state encoded in a radio signal.
 It's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smart
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in that it's a computer, able to track it's own position in a given coordinate
 chart.
 It can then encode this info in a transmitted radio signal, which travels
 along a null geodesic, until it intersects with the observer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Encoded information should include:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The proper time, as perceived by the flashlight.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The coordinates of the flashlight, at the time that it emitted the signal.
 They encode the coordinates of the flashlight at the time of signal emission.
 These coordinates are expressed in whatever convenient coordinate system
 we'll use.
 Currently, Gullstrand–Painlevé coordinates seem like a good choice; see
 below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 4-velocity of the flashlight, at the time of the signal emission.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The direction the flashlight was facing, in full: all three Euler coords
 (or whatever coord system is being employed.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The initial location and velocity of the flashlight.
 That is, the flashlight is assumed to start falling freely only after it
 has been boosted into some particular trajectory.
 The starting point can be anywhere outside tthe event horizon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The observer likewise falls freely, after being boosted to some initial
 starting trajectory.
 The observer looks at the flashlight, and makes a note of the signal that
 it is receiving.
 This includes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The direction from which the flashlight signal came from.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The polarization of the flashlight signal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The redshift of the flashlight signal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both the flashlight and the observer fall with time-like geodesics.
 The flashlight signal is, of course, follows a null geodesic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More precisely, we imagine a single observer embeded in a cloud of freely-fallin
g 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smart dust
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: a distribution of such flashlights, flying every-which way.
 We wish to observe and analyze the plethora of incomging signals: to make
 a movie of what the observer sees, in the observers proper time.
\end_layout

