\begin_layout Section
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal is to get some insight into the firewall problem.
 Lets recap this, in the most naive way possible.
 Some(?) classic GR texts ask 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

what happens when an astronaut falls through the event horizon?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and then provide an answer: not much, for a galactic-sized black hole.
 This argument rests on the idea that tidal forces are small/un-noticable,
 and that the lab frame is approximately flat, ergo nothing happens.
 This argument seems entirely self-consistent.
 Mathematically, we imagine some tangent plane (that defines the lab frame)
 falling across the horizon, and all is fine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is contradicted by another thought experiment.
 Suppose the astronaut is carrying a head-lamp, that illuminates his hands
 and feet, so he can 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

see what he's doing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Perhaps wearing a glow-in-the-dark suit.
 Suppose he dives, hands first, so that the hands cross the EH before the
 eyes.
 Can he see his hands? Well, he should not be able to, as they are on the
 other side of the EH.
 There aren't any null outgoing geodesics.
 Once his head crosses the EH, can he see his hands again? Is there a breif
 flash, and then he can see normally again? I think not; I think they remain
 dark.
 They have fallen into the future, and stay there.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This second picture is deeply disturbing for survivability.
 Lets replace the astronaut by a robot, so we can talk aout a mechanical,
 say, steel arm, that gets it's rigidity from atomic forces.
 Rigid motion propagates at the speed of sound, which is determined by the
 Young's modulus for steel, and we can hand wave 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

its electromagnetic forces between the atoms
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, whatever that means.
 It would appear that the robot's arms, having crossed the EH, must suffer
 mechanical failure, as no stress signal can propagate back up the bar of
 steel.
 It surely gets shredded.
 In terms of reference frames, I think it's correct to say that the arm
 has rotated into the future, and causality is such that the future cannot
 affect the past: the arm has dettached.
 This reasoning goes down to the atomic scales: it seems the shredding happens
 at the atomic scale.
 This is, I presume, the origin of the firewall idea.
 But it seems entirely at odds with the idea that the lab frame falls unharmed
 through the EH.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So which is it? Studying the infall of smart dust seems to be the way to
 do it.
 There are several levels of questions here.
 First, and most direct: given any two points on the manifold, does there
 exist a null ge
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
wearing a glow-in-the-dark suit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
phenomenon we wish to study is the appearance of dynamic horizons: some
 of the dust will move beyond a horizon, in that there will not be any null
 geodesics that connect those flashlights to the observer.
 We want to study the shape of that horizon.
 In particular, we want to study the shape of this horizon as the observer
 nears and falls through the Schwarschild radius.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why is this interesting? Well, the smart dust can be thought of as forming
 a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

virtual robot
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Rather than being mechanical, its a cloud.
 What happens to that cloud? It seems clear that as parts of it fall beyond
 the dynamic horizon, it becomes 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shreaded
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, imagine that this dust implements a virtual, smart differential-equation
 solver.
 Each dust particle comminucates with it's nearest neighbors, using null
 geodesics, to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

solve
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 some diffeq.
 The dynamic horizons will shred this fabric.
 How? I'm not sure this idea of a diff-eq is well-founded: the conventinoal
 idea is that there's some lab frame that is approx flat in some small-enough
 region, and we can always just solve normal diffeqs where its flat.
 Yet, somehow, atoms are electromagnetic; mechanical forces propagate at
 the speed of sound, and the shredding of the dynamic horizon is ...
 well.
 I'm tangled and confused here.
 So, understanding the dynamic horizons seems like the appropriate first
 step.
\end_layout

